@c    THE HOLY GOSPEL OF JESUS CHRIST ACCORDING TO ST. LUKE



@c    St. Luke was a native of Antioch, the capital of Syria.  He was by
@c    profession a physician; and some ancient writers say, that he was very
@c    skillful in painting.  He was converted by St. Paul and became his
@c    disciple and companion in his travels, and fellow-labourer in the
@c    ministry of the Gospel.  He wrote in Greek, about twenty-four years
@c    after our Lord's Ascension.



@c    Luke Chapter 1


@c    The conception of John the Baptist, and of Christ.  The visitation and
@c    canticle of the Blessed Virgin.  The birth of the Baptist and the
@c    canticle of Zachary.

@c    1:1. Forasmuch as many have taken in hand to set forth in order a
@c    narration of the things that have been accomplished among us,

@c    1:2. According as they have delivered them unto us, who from the
@c    beginning were eyewitnesses and ministers of the word:

@c    1:3. It seemed good to me also, having diligently attained to all
@c    things from the beginning, to write to thee in order, most excellent
@c    Theophilus,

@c    1:4. That thou mayest know the verity of those words in which thou hast
@c    been instructed.

@c    1:5. There was in the days of Herod, the king of Judea, a certain
@c    priest named Zachary, of the course of Abia:  and his wife was of the
@c    daughters of Aaron, and her name Elizabeth.

@c    Of the course of Abia. . .that is, of the rank of Abia, which word in
@c    the Greek is commonly put for the employment of one day:  but here for
@c    the functions of a whole week.  For, by the appointment of David, 1 Par.
@c    24., the descendants from Aaron were divided into twenty-four families,
@c    of which the eighth was Abia, from whom descended this Zachary, who at
@c    this time was in the week of his priestly functions.

@c    1:6. And they were both just before God, walking in all the
@c    commandments and justifications of the Lord without blame.

@c    1:7. And they had no son, for that Elizabeth was barren:  and they both
@c    were well advanced in years.

@c    1:8. And it came to pass, when he executed the priestly function in the
@c    order of his course before God,

@c    1:9. According to the custom of the priestly office, it was his lot to
@c    offer incense, going into the temple of the Lord.

@c    1:10. And all the multitude of the people was praying without, at the
@c    hour of incense.

@c    1:11. And there appeared to him an angel of the Lord, standing on the
@c    right side of the altar of incense.

@c    1:12. And Zachary seeing him, was troubled:  and fear fell upon him.

@c    1:13. But the angel said to him:  Fear not, Zachary, for thy prayer is
@c    heard:  and thy wife Elizabeth shall bear thee a son.  And thou shalt
@c    call his name John.

@c    1:14. And thou shalt have joy and gladness:  and many shall rejoice in
@c    his nativity.

@c    1:15. For he shall be great before the Lord and shall drink no wine nor
@c    strong drink:  and he shall be filled with the Holy Ghost, even from his
@c    mother's womb.

@c    1:16. And he shall convert many of the children of Israel to the Lord
@c    their God.

@c    1:17. And he shall go before him in the spirit and power of Elias:  that
@c    he may turn the hearts of the fathers unto the children and the
@c    incredulous to the wisdom of the just, to prepare unto the Lord a
@c    perfect people.

@c    1:18. And Zachary said to the angel:  Whereby shall I know this?  For I
@c    am an old man, and my wife is advanced in years.

@c    1:19. And the angel answering, said to him:  I am Gabriel, who stand
@c    before God and am sent to speak to thee and to bring thee these good
@c    tidings.

@c    1:20. And behold, thou shalt be dumb and shalt not be able to speak
@c    until the day wherein these things shall come to pass:  because thou
@c    hast not believed my words, which shall be fulfilled in their time.

@c    1:21. And the people were waiting for Zachary:  and they wondered that
@c    he tarried so long in the temple.

@c    1:22. And when he came out, he could not speak to them:  and they
@c    understood that he had seen a vision in the temple.  And he made signs
@c    to them and remained dumb.

@c    1:23. And it came to pass, after the days of his office were
@c    accomplished, he departed to his own house.

@c    1:24. And after those days, Elizabeth his wife conceived and hid
@c    herself five months, saying:

@c    1:25. Thus hath the Lord dealt with me in the days wherein he hath had
@c    regard to take away my reproach among men.

@c    1:26. And in the sixth month, the angel Gabriel was sent from God into
@c    a city of Galilee, called Nazareth,

@c    1:27. To a virgin espoused to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house
@c    of David:  and the virgin's name was Mary.

@c    1:28. And the angel being come in, said unto her:  Hail, full of grace,
@c    the Lord is with thee:  blessed art thou among women.

@c    1:29. Who having heard, was troubled at his saying and thought with
@c    herself what manner of salutation this should be.

@c    1:30. And the angel said to her:  Fear not, Mary, for thou hast found
@c    grace with God.

@c    1:31. Behold thou shalt conceive in thy womb and shalt bring forth a
@c    son:  and thou shalt call his name Jesus.

@c    1:32. He shall be great and shall be called the Son of the Most High.
@c    And the Lord God shall give unto him the throne of David his father:
@c    and he shall reign in the house of Jacob for ever.

@c    1:33. And of his kingdom there shall be no end.

@c    1:34. And Mary said to the angel:  How shall this be done, because I
@c    know not man?

@c    1:35. And the angel answering, said to her:  The Holy Ghost shall come
@c    upon thee and the power of the Most High shall overshadow thee.  And
@c    therefore also the Holy which shall be born of thee shall be called the
@c    Son of God.

@c    1:36. And behold thy cousin Elizabeth, she also hath conceived a son in
@c    her old age:  and this is the sixth month with her that is called
@c    barren.

@c    1:37. Because no word shall be impossible with God.

@c    1:38. And Mary said:  Behold the handmaid of the Lord:  be it done to me
@c    according to thy word.  And the angel departed from her.

@c    1:39. And Mary rising up in those days, went into the hill country with
@c    haste into a city of Juda.

@c    1:40. And she entered into the house of Zachary and saluted Elizabeth.

@c    1:41. And it came to pass that when Elizabeth heard the salutation of
@c    Mary, the infant leaped in her womb.  And Elizabeth was filled with the
@c    Holy Ghost.

@c    1:42. And she cried out with a loud voice and said:  Blessed art thou
@c    among women and blessed is the fruit of thy womb.

@c    1:43. And whence is this to me that the mother of my Lord should come
@c    to me?

@c    1:44. For behold as soon as the voice of thy salutation sounded in my
@c    ears, the infant in my womb leaped for joy.

@c    1:45. And blessed art thou that hast believed, because those things
@c    shall be accomplished that were spoken to thee by the Lord.

@c    1:46. And Mary said:  My soul doth magnify the Lord.

@c    1:47. And my spirit hath rejoiced in God my Saviour.

@c    1:48. Because he hath regarded the humility of his handmaid:  for behold
@c    from henceforth all generations shall call me blessed.

@c    Shall call me blessed. . .These words are a prediction of that honour
@c    which the church in all ages should pay to the Blessed Virgin.  Let
@c    Protestants examine whether they are any way concerned in this
@c    prophecy.

@c    1:49. Because he that is mighty hath done great things to me:  and holy
@c    is his name.

@c    1:50. And his mercy is from generation unto generations, to them that
@c    fear him.

@c    1:51. He hath shewed might in his arm:  he hath scattered the proud in
@c    the conceit of their heart.

@c    1:52. He hath put down the mighty from their seat and hath exalted the
@c    humble.

@c    1:53. He hath filled the hungry with good things:  and the rich he hath
@c    sent empty away.

@c    1:54. He hath received Israel his servant, being mindful of his mercy.

@c    1:55. As he spoke to our fathers:  to Abraham and to his seed for ever.

@c    1:56. And Mary abode with her about three months.  And she returned to
@c    her own house.

@c    1:57. Now Elizabeth's full time of being delivered was come:  and she
@c    brought forth a son.

@c    1:58. And her neighbors and kinsfolks heard that the Lord had shewed
@c    his great mercy towards her:  and they congratulated with her.

@c    1:59. And it came to pass that on the eighth day they came to
@c    circumcise the child:  and they called him by his father's name Zachary.

@c    1:60. And his mother answering, said:  Not so.  But he shall be called
@c    John.

@c    1:61. And they said to her:  There is none of thy kindred that is called
@c    by this name.

@c    1:62. And they made signs to his father, how he would have him called.

@c    1:63. And demanding a writing table, he wrote, saying:  John is his
@c    name.  And they all wondered.

@c    1:64. And immediately his mouth was opened and his tongue loosed:  and
@c    he spoke, blessing God.

@c    1:65. And fear came upon all their neighbours:  and all these things
@c    were noised abroad over all the hill country of Judea.

@c    1:66. And all they that had heard them laid them up in their heart,
@c    saying:  What an one, think ye, shall this child be?  For the hand of the
@c    Lord was with him.

@c    1:67. And Zachary his father was filled with the Holy Ghost.  And he
@c    prophesied, saying:

@c    1:68. Blessed be the Lord God of Israel:  because he hath visited and
@c    wrought the redemption of his people.

@c    1:69. And hath raised up an horn of salvation to us, in the house of
@c    David his servant.

@c    Horn of salvation. . .That is, A powerful salvation, as Dr.  Witham
@c    translates it.  For in the Scripture, by horn is generally understood
@c    strength and power.

@c    1:70. As he spoke by the mouth of his holy prophets, who are from the
@c    beginning.

@c    1:71. Salvation from our enemies and from the hand of all that hate us.

@c    1:72. To perform mercy to our fathers and to remember his holy
@c    testament.

@c    1:73. The oath, which he swore to Abraham our father, that he would
@c    grant to us.

@c    1:74. That being delivered from the hand of our enemies, we may serve
@c    him without fear:

@c    1:75. In holiness and justice before him, all our days.

@c    1:76. And thou, child, shalt be called the prophet of the Highest:  for
@c    thou shalt, go before the face of the Lord to prepare his ways:

@c    1:77. To give knowledge of salvation to his people, unto the remission
@c    of their sins.

@c    1:78. Through the bowels of the mercy of our God, in which the Orient
@c    from on high hath visited us:

@c    The Orient. . .It is one of the titles of the Messias, the true light of
@c    the world, and the sun of justice.

@c    1:79. To enlighten them that sit in darkness and in the shadow of
@c    death:  to direct our feet into the way of peace.

@c    1:80. And the child grew and was strengthened in spirit:  and was in the
@c    deserts until the day of his manifestation to Israel.



@c    Luke Chapter 2


@c    The birth of Christ.  His presentation in the temple.  Simeon's prophecy.
@c    Christ at twelve years of age, is found amongst the doctors.

@c    2:1. And it came to pass that in those days there went out a decree
@c    from Caesar Augustus that the whole world should be enrolled.

@c    2:2. This enrolling was first made by Cyrinus, the governor of Syria.

@c    2:3. And all went to be enrolled, every one into his own city.

@c    2:4. And Joseph also went up from Galilee, out of the city of Nazareth,
@c    into Judea, to the city of David, which is called Bethlehem:  because he
@c    was of the house and family of David.

@c    2:5. To be enrolled with Mary his espoused wife, who was with child.

@c    2:6. And it came to pass that when they were there, her days were
@c    accomplished that she should be delivered.

@c    2:7. And she brought forth her first born son and wrapped him up in
@c    swaddling clothes and laid him in a manger:  because there was no room
@c    for them in the inn.

@c    Her firstborn. . .The meaning is, not that she had afterward any other
@c    child; but it is a way of speech among the Hebrews, to call them also
@c    the firstborn, who are the only children.  See annotation Matt. 1. 25.

@c    2:8. And there were in the same country shepherds watching and keeping
@c    the night watches over their flock.

@c    2:9. And behold an angel of the Lord stood by them and the brightness
@c    of God shone round about them:  and they feared with a great fear.

@c    2:10. And the angel said to them:  Fear not; for, behold, I bring you
@c    good tidings of great joy that shall be to all the people:

@c    2:11. For, this day is born to you a Saviour, who is Christ the Lord,
@c    in the city of David.

@c    2:12. And this shall be a sign unto you.  You shall find the infant
@c    wrapped in swaddling clothes and laid in a manger.

@c    2:13. And suddenly there was with the angel a multitude of the heavenly
@c    army, praising God and saying:

@c    2:14. Glory to God in the highest:  and on earth peace to men of good
@c    will.

@c    2:15. And it came to pass, after the angels departed from them into
@c    heaven, the shepherds said one to another:  Let us go over to Bethlehem
@c    and let us see this word that is come to pass, which the Lord hath
@c    shewed to us.

@c    2:16. And they came with haste:  and they found Mary and Joseph, and the
@c    infant lying in the manger.

@c    2:17. And seeing, they understood of the word that had been spoken to
@c    them concerning this child.

@c    2:18. And all that heard wondered:  and at those things that were told
@c    them by the shepherds.

@c    2:19. But Mary kept all these words, pondering them in her heart.

@c    2:20. And the shepherds returned, glorifying and praising God for all
@c    the things they had heard and seen, as it was told unto them.

@c    2:21. And after eight days were accomplished, that the child should be
@c    circumcised, his name was called JESUS, which was called by the angel
@c    before he was conceived in the womb.

@c    2:22. And after the days of her purification, according to the law of
@c    Moses, were accomplished, they carried him to Jerusalem, to present him
@c    to the Lord:

@c    2:23. As it is written in the law of the Lord:  Every male opening the
@c    womb shall be called holy to the Lord:

@c    2:24. And to offer a sacrifice, according as it is written in the law
@c    of the Lord, a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons:

@c    2:25. And behold there was a man in Jerusalem named Simeon:  and this
@c    man was just and devout, waiting for the consolation of Israel.  And the
@c    Holy Ghost was in him.

@c    2:26. And he had received an answer from the Holy Ghost, that he should
@c    not see death before he had seen the Christ of the Lord.

@c    2:27. And he came by the Spirit into the temple.  And when his parents
@c    brought in the child Jesus, to do for him according to the custom of
@c    the law,

@c    2:28. He also took him into his arms and blessed God and said

@c    2:29. Now thou dost dismiss thy servant, O Lord, according to thy word
@c    in peace:

@c    2:30. Because my eyes have seen thy salvation,

@c    2:31. Which thou hast prepared before the face of all peoples:

@c    2:32. A light to the revelation of the Gentiles and the glory of thy
@c    people Israel.

@c    2:33. And his father and mother were wondering at those things which
@c    were spoken concerning him.

@c    2:34. And Simeon blessed them and said to Mary his mother:  Behold this
@c    child is set for the fall and for the resurrection of many in Israel
@c    and for a sign which shall be contradicted.

@c    For the fall, etc. . .Christ came for the salvation of all men; but here
@c    Simeon prophesies what would come to pass, that many through their own
@c    wilful blindness and obstinacy would not believe in Christ, nor receive
@c    his doctrine, which therefore would be ruin to them:  but to others a
@c    resurrection, by their believing in him, and obeying his commandments.

@c    2:35. And thy own soul a sword shall pierce, that, out of many hearts
@c    thoughts may be revealed.

@c    2:36. And there was one Anna, a prophetess, the daughter of Phanuel, of
@c    the tribe of Aser.  She was far advanced in years and had lived with her
@c    husband seven years from her virginity.

@c    2:37. And she was a widow until fourscore and four years:  who departed
@c    not from the temple, by fastings and prayers serving night and day.

@c    2:38. Now she, at the same hour, coming in, confessed to the Lord:  and
@c    spoke of him to all that looked for the redemption of Israel.

@c    2:39. And after they had performed all things according to the law of
@c    the Lord, they returned into Galilee, to their city Nazareth.

@c    2:40. And the child grew and waxed strong, full of wisdom:  and the
@c    grace of God was in him.

@c    2:41. And his parents went every year to Jerusalem, at the solemn day
@c    of the pasch.

@c    2:42. And when he was twelve years old, they going up into Jerusalem,
@c    according to the custom of the feast,

@c    2:43. And having fulfilled the days, when they returned, the child
@c    Jesus remained in Jerusalem.  And his parents knew it not.

@c    2:44. And thinking that he was in the company, they came a day's
@c    journey and sought him among their kinsfolks and acquaintance.

@c    2:45. And not finding him, they returned into Jerusalem, seeking him.

@c    2:46. And it came to pass, that, after three days, they found him in
@c    the temple, sitting in the midst of the doctors, hearing them and
@c    asking them questions.

@c    2:47. And all that heard him were astonished at his wisdom and his
@c    answers.

@c    2:48. And seeing him, they wondered.  And his mother said to him:  Son,
@c    why hast thou done so to us?  Behold thy father and I have sought thee
@c    sorrowing.

@c    2:49. And he said to them:  How is it that you sought me?  Did you not
@c    know that I must be about my father's business?

@c    2:50. And they understood not the word that he spoke unto them.

@c    2:51. And he went down with them and came to Nazareth and was subject
@c    to them.  And his mother kept all these words in her heart.

@c    2:52. And Jesus advanced in wisdom and age and grace with God and men.



@c    Luke Chapter 3


@c    John's mission and preaching.  Christ is baptized by him.

@c    3:1. Now in the fifteenth year of the reign of Tiberius Caesar, Pontius
@c    Pilate being governor of Judea, and Herod being tetrarch of Galilee,
@c    and Philip his brother tetrarch of Iturea and the country of
@c    Trachonitis, and Lysanias tetrarch of Abilina:

@c    3:2. Under the high priests Anna and Caiphas:  the word of the Lord was
@c    made unto John, the son of Zachary, in the desert.

@c    3:3. And he came into all the country about the Jordan, preaching the
@c    baptism of penance for the remission of sins.

@c    3:4. As it was written in the book of the sayings of Isaias the
@c    prophet:  A voice of one crying in the wilderness:  Prepare ye the way of
@c    the Lord, make straight his paths.

@c    3:5. Every valley shall be filled and every mountain and hill shall be
@c    brought low:  and the crooked shall be made straight, and the rough ways
@c    plain.

@c    3:6. And all flesh shall see the salvation of God.

@c    3:7. He said therefore to the multitudes that went forth to be baptized
@c    by him:  Ye offspring of vipers, who hath shewed you to flee from the
@c    wrath to come?

@c    3:8. Bring forth therefore fruits worthy of penance:  and do not begin
@c    to say, We have Abraham for our father.  For I say unto you that God is
@c    able of these stones, to raise up children to Abraham.

@c    3:9. For now the axe is laid to the root of the trees.  Every tree
@c    therefore that bringeth not forth good fruit shall be cut down and cast
@c    into the fire.

@c    3:10. And the people asked him, saying:  What then shall we do?

@c    3:11. And he answering, said to them:  He that hath two coats, let him
@c    give to him that hath none; and he that hath meat, let him do in like
@c    manner.

@c    3:12. And the publicans also came to be baptized and said to him:
@c    Master, what shall we do?

@c    3:13. But he said to them:  Do nothing more than that which is appointed
@c    you.

@c    3:14. And the soldiers also asked him, saying:  And what shall we do?
@c    And he said to them:  Do violence to no man, neither calumniate any man;
@c    and be content with your pay.

@c    3:15. And as the people were of opinion, and all were thinking in their
@c    hearts of John, that perhaps he might be the Christ:

@c    3:16. John answered, saying unto all:  I indeed baptize you with water:
@c    but there shall come one mightier than I, the latchet of whose shoes I
@c    am not worthy to loose.  He shall baptize you with the Holy Ghost and
@c    with fire;

@c    3:17. Whose fan is in his hand:  and he will purge his floor and will
@c    gather the wheat into his barn:  but the chaff he will burn with
@c    unquenchable fire.

@c    3:18. And many other things exhorting did he preach to the people.

@c    3:19. But Herod the tetrarch, when he was reproved by him for Herodias,
@c    his brother's wife, and for all the evils which Herod had done:

@c    3:20. He added this also above all and shut up John in prison.

@c    3:21. Now it came to pass, when all the people were baptized, that
@c    Jesus also being baptized and praying, heaven was opened.

@c    3:22. And the Holy Ghost descended in a bodily shape, as a dove, upon
@c    him.  And a voice came from heaven:  Thou art my beloved Son.  In thee I
@c    am well pleased.

@c    3:23. And Jesus himself was beginning about the age of thirty years:
@c    being (as it was supposed) the son of Joseph, who was of Heli, who was
@c    of Mathat,

@c    Who was of Heli. . .St. Joseph, who by nature was the son of Jacob, (St.
@c    Matt. 1. 16,) in the account of the law, was son of Heli.  For Heli and
@c    Jacob were brothers, by the same mother; and Heli, who was the elder,
@c    dying without issue, Jacob, as the law directed, married his widow:  in
@c    consequence of such marriage, his son Joseph was reputed in the law the
@c    son of Heli.

@c    3:24. Who was of Levi, who was of Melchi.  who was of Janne, who was of
@c    Joseph,

@c    3:25. Who was of Mathathias, who was of Amos, who was of Nahum, who was
@c    of Hesli, who was of Nagge,

@c    3:26. Who was of Mahath, who was of Mathathias, who was of Semei, who
@c    was of Joseph, who was of Juda,

@c    3:27. Who was of Joanna, who was of Reza, who was of Zorobabel, who was
@c    of Salathiel, who was of Neri,

@c    3:28. Who was of Melchi, who was of Addi, who was of Cosan, who was of
@c    Helmadan, who was of Her,

@c    3:29. Who was of Jesus, who was of Eliezer, who was of Jorim, who was
@c    of Mathat, who was of Levi,

@c    3:30. Who was of Simeon, who was of Judas, who was of Joseph, who was
